CHAPTER 9\par
JUST ONE OF THE CROWD\par
\par
Jeff decided, after numerous glances back over his shoulder, that he had finally lost his pursuit. He had run blindly, turning corners and dodging behind robots and vehicles and buildings every time he could, before slowing down. He was not out of breath, or even tired, but he was disoriented and scared.\par
He didn\'92t know where he was going, or even why he had run. Right now, he just wanted to be alone. He eyed warily other robots that he passed, but they paid him no particular attention.  Either the medical staff had not yet put any word out, or his physical traits carried no designation they could use to identify him. The thought that he would not have to run every minute bolstered his spirits a little. The total lack of humans dampened them again.\par
The entire situation just didn\'92t seem real. It was absurd. How could he, Jeff Leong, eighteen years old,  recently accepted into college, a healthy and fairly normal Auroran...be a robot?\par
He walked. He walked straight, turned corners and then found a slidewalk and got on it. With nowhere to go and nothing to do, he just kept walking along the slidewalk.\par
At first, his senses were still askew. His eyes were not only more sensitive than before, but they seemed to see in a much wider range of the spectrum. He found himself looking at colors,  as he termed them, that he had never seen before and had no name for\'97and they unnerved him. Gradually, he learned to shut out most of the unwanted light waves. The same had occurred with his hearing. It had been so acute at first that all sounds had reached him in a kind of jumble. Then he had been able, by concentrating, to reduce his hearing acuity to a level that felt comfortable.  He had been intrigued by the added abilities, but he would have to learn how to control them.\par
The walking also helped him become more familiar with his new body. It responded smoothly and efficiently,  with good balance and control. He couldn\'92t complain about that. Before long, he had concluded that he was moving enough like the other robots, the real ones,  to escape notice.\par
He also looked over the robots he passed, as nonchalantly as he could, in search of identifying marks. The robots bore differences, certainly, especially where job-related equipment was concerned on the non-humanoid ones. He saw several distinct but subtle pattern differences repeated on many of the humanoid robots, and guessed they represented minor engineering improvements on robots that had been made or repaired at different times. If they had individual identification, however, he was too much of a stranger here to see it.\par
Gradually, he found himself moving in a consistent direction. The population seemed denser that way,  perhaps toward the center of the urban area. All the robots seemed intent on their own occupations, and he grew more confident that he could lose himself in the crowd.\par
Yet, he still had nothing to do and nowhere to go.\par
Ahead of him, through a crowd of robots, he thought he saw a girl, or young woman, emerge from some kind of underground entrance. With a surge of excitement, he quickened his pace and leaned to one side to look between two other robots. When they glanced at him,  he straightened in alarm.\par
He could see her walking the other way. If he wanted to avoid notice, he would have to act with the same deliberate manner as all the robots around him. He lengthened his stride and gave chase without otherwise altering his body language.\par
Not far ahead, she had stopped to speak to a robot. Jeff slowed down as he approached, and stopped when her back was to him. He was a good distance away by human standards, but after a moment of effort, he was able to sharpen his hearing enough to eavesdrop.\par
\'93Identify yourself,\'94 she was saying.\par
\'93I am Tunnel Foreman 41,\'94 said the robot.\par
\'93I\'92m Ariel. Please spread the word about the First Law obligation I\'92ve described.\'94\par
\'93I must,\'94 said Tunnel Foreman 41.\par
The robot departed and Ariel started to go. Then she saw Jeff watching her, and she paused.\par
\'93The First Law?\'94 Jeff asked. He wanted to continue his masquerade as a robot until he knew something about her.\par
\'93Yes,\'94 said Ariel. \'93We\'92re looking for two people who are probably starving in Robot City. One is a child traveling with a robot and the other is alone. The First Law requires that all robots help locate them.\'94\par
\'93Of course,\'94 said Jeff, suddenly realizing that of course this did not apply to him. He still had his human brain, and the imperative of the Laws was located in the positronic brains of the robots. Yet if he revealed this, his identity would be known to anyone aware of the transplant and his subsequent escape.\par
\'93Report any sightings of them to the central computer,\'94 Ariel went on. \'93Detain them if you can, without violating the Laws. We\'92ll see that they\'92re fed.\'94\par
\'93I understand,\'94 said Jeff. He was trying frantically to think of a question, anything, to learn more about her without giving himself away.\par
\'93Identify,\'94 she said.\par
\'93Uh\'97Tunnel Foreman 12.\'94 He couldn\'92t risk making up a job, in case she would recognize the fraud. \'93Do you know who they are?\'94\par
\'93Why, no.\'94 She looked at him in some surprise. \'93They just seem to have landed and walked into the city. In fact, if you come across them, find out what you can about their spacecraft.\'94\par
\'93Find out what?\'94\par
\'93Well, where it is, if it\'92s damaged, what kind it is....\'94 She cocked her head to one side. \'93None of the other robots have asked these questions.\'94\par
Jeff felt the impulse to run wash over him again, but he couldn\'92t afford to look like a fugitive. He forced himself to remain where he was, searching for something to say.\par
\'93Tell me why your responses are different.\'94\par
He knew why she had changed her observation to an instruction. Now he, under the Second Law, was required to answer, or else blow his cover if he didn\'92t. The scarcity of humans in this weird place\'97the only fact about it that he was sure of\'97would mean he wouldn\'92t have to go through this very often.\par
\'93I cannot judge the responses of others,\'94 he said, picking his phrases carefully. \'93My responses are based on a desire to elicit further information that may be of help.\'94\par
