\'93Really?\'94 Jeff was surprised.  \'93Just to see me?\'94\par
\'93\'91U\'92ve been alone on Robot City.  Only one of \'91urr kind. I know about that. \'91U could be sick and can\'92t tell.  Could find out.\'94\par
Jeff looked up at the ceiling. He had been feeling lonely, now that she mentioned it. Maybe he was sick.\par
\'93I don\'92t trust them,\'94 he said to Wolruf. \'93I can take over this city\'97this whole planet. They want to stop me.\'94  The fire was gone, though; he felt it himself. He was tired, emotionally tired.\par
\'93Robots can\'92t \'91urt \'91u on purpose,\'94 she reminded him. \'93Make rare mistakes, but can\'92t \'91urt \'91uman on purpose.\'94\par
\'93Derec and Ariel\'97\'94\par
\'93Robots can\'92t allow them to \'91urt \'91u, either.  Test can tell \'91u if \'91urr sick or not.\'94\par
Jeff closed his eyes and sighed.\par
\par
Derec hadn\'92t seen Wolruf leave the group in the testing room, but he noticed her come back in. The little alien bore her distinctive teeth-baring grin when she looked up at him.\par
\'93What is it, Wolruf?\'94 He asked.\par
\'93Jeff changed \'91is mind. Will take test now.\'94\par
Everyone turned to look at her.\par
\'93Are you certain?\'94 asked Research 1.\par
\'93I\'92ve underestimated you before,\'94 said Derec. \'93Remind me not to do it again.\'94\par
\'93Wolruf? How did you manage that?\'94 Ariel asked in astonishment.\par
\'93Just talked to \'91im,\'94 said Wolruf. \'93Suggest \'91u don\'92t talk to \'91im, or \'91e\'92ll change \'91is mind.\'94\par
\'93We\'92ll take your word for it,\'94  said Derec. \'93Research 1, you and Surgeon 1 go ahead and run your tests. I suggest that you also conduct a minimum of conversation with him. I guess he\'92s still pretty unpredictable.\'94\par
\'93I will begin the procedures with Jeff,\'94 said Research 1. \'93May I request that you allow Surgeon 1 to conduct the scans of your body that we have already discussed? The equipment is prepared, and the central computer will benefit from the information regardless of Jeff\'92s condition and wishes.\'94\par
\'93Sure.\'94 Derec turned to Ariel and Mandelbrot. \'93As soon as I\'92m finished\'97\'94\par
\'93Right. We\'92ll be here,\'94 she said with a grin. \'93Wolruf, too.\'94\par
Derec followed Surgeon 1 into a cramped room and stretched out, undressed, on a cold platform at the robot\'92s bidding. The robot attached a variety of sensors to him, all connected to some of the worst looking jury-rigged equipment Derec had seen on this planet. For once, the necessity for speed had overcome the values of minimalist engineering; the robots had put together something that would work, ignoring convenience and appearance.\par
As Surgeon 1 ran various vibrations through parts of his body and shot him with invisible rays, Derec assured himself that once the emergency with Jeff was past, they would either improve the engineering of this equipment or discard it altogether. They weren\'92t likely to allow an anomaly like this to remain as it was. Still, he felt a sense of petty satisfaction in seeing that they weren\'92t always perfect.\par
When the scans were finished,  Derec got dressed as Surgeon 1 glanced over the monitors.\par
\'93This is sufficient,\'94 said Surgeon 1. \'93We are capable of restoring Jeff\'92s body to a state of health,  granted his normal recuperative powers after surgery. Research 1 has contacted me through his comlink, and requests our presence back in the testing room.\'94\par
Research 1 was waiting when they got there. \'93Well?\'94 Derec said. \'93How is he?\'94\par
\'93Ariel\'92s theory appears to be correct. The level of several hormones that can affect mood and behavior in humans were higher than we had intended. Given the limited blood supply, very small amounts skew the percentages.\'94\par
\'93I was sure he wasn\'92t that bad a guy,\'94 said Ariel.\par
\'93Me, too,\'94 said Wolruf.\par
\'93What are you going to do,  though?\'94 Derec asked. \'93Have you discussed this with him yet?\'94\par
\'93No. Surgeon 1 and I must confer over the details. If Surgeon 1 agrees with me, then Jeff Leong is not responsible for his behavior. In that event, we would take the position that our judgment of his condition under the First Law would override all his orders to us under the Second Law.\'94\par
\'93Whew,\'94 said Ariel. \'93That\'92s a very big step.\'94\par
\'93I think,\'94 said Derec, \'93that it\'92s time for us to take care of some personal business. Research 1, do you need further human assistance at the moment? If not, we have an important errand to run.\'94\par
\'93We do not require your assistance at this time,\'94 said Research 1. \'93I request your return later in the day.\'94\par
\'93No problem.\'94 Derec turned to Mandelbrot with a big grin. \'93Okay, friend. Show us this spacecraft you have waiting. I\'92ll have to check its condition and facilities and all. Where is it?\'94\par
\'93It is in a rural area just outside the urban perimeter. One of the tunnels will take us close to the spot.\'94\par
\'93Let\'92s go\'97you, Wolruf, Ariel and me.\'94\par
The trip out to the perimeter was uneventful, except for the glow of excitement that Derec and Ariel shared.  Once they reached the construction perimeter, they had to start hiking.  Fortunately, Mandelbrot had chosen a broad, open field for his landing, with only a short cushion of broad-bladed, blue ground cover.\par
\'93I see it!\'94 Ariel shouted,  pointing to a sliver of blue-silver glinting in the sunlight. It was just beyond a gentle rise in the terrain.\par
Derec looked up eagerly, then felt a sudden weight of disappointment, even though it was still mostly out of sight. He didn\'92t say anything, though, until they had topped the rise and were looking down on the sleek, undamaged craft. Ariel, too, stopped in surprise.\par
\'93It\'92s a lifepod,\'94 Derec said dully. It was so small that even the gently rolling ground had hidden it almost completely.\par
\'93Correct,\'94 said Mandelbrot. \'93A somewhat converted lifepod. I modified it.\'94\par
\'93Alpha,\'94 said Derec, shaking his head. \'93Mandelbrot, I mean.\'94\par
\'93I detect distress,\'94 said Mandelbrot. \'93What is its cause?\'94\par
\'93Whatever your name is,\'94 Ariel wailed, \'93we wanted to get out of here. But this little ship only has room for one.\'94\par
\'93I traveled with \'91im,\'94 said Wolruf.\par
\'93Mandelbrot, why didn\'92t you tell us it could only carry one full-sized humanoid?\'94 Derec asked. \'93I asked you where it was, what condition it was in, and so on.\'94\par
\'93The only subject of discussion at that time was the welfare of Jeff Leong. I surmised that you wanted it for his use. It is adequate for that purpose.\'94\par
\'93Yeah.\'94 Derec sighed. \'93So it is.\'94 He slipped an arm casually around Ariel\'92s shoulders. \'93I think it\'92s more important to get Ariel off the planet, though. She has\'97something to take care of.\'94\par
She took his hand and squeezed it,  probably for not mentioning her disease in particular.\par
\'93How did you modify it?\'94 Derec asked.\par
\'93I was able to give it a significant drive ability. Also, I was able to create space for Wolruf. I myself used the space principally intended for human use, but of course I do not have the supply requirements. The supply space was available for her provisions.\'94\par
Derec nodded, staring silently at the little ship. No one else spoke. They all seemed to understand the realization, and what it meant to him. Finally, when he turned away, they followed him back to the tunnel stop without a word.\par
By the time they returned to the facility, Research 1 and Surgeon 1 were just leaving the O.R.\par
\'93Are you finished already?\'94  Ariel asked in surprise. \'93How is he?\'94\par
\'93The procedures have apparently been successful so far,\'94 said Surgeon 1. \'93Unlike the transplantation into his robot body, which required no recovery period, his human body will require an extended recuperative phase with close attention from us.\'94\par
\'93The most important unknown factor now is his biological recuperative power, with which we have little experience,\'94 said Research 1. \'93However, we\'97\'94\par
\'93You think he\'92ll be okay,\'94 Derec interpreted. \'93Right?\'94\par
\'93Correct,\'94 said Research 1.\par
\'93What about his, well, his attitude?\'94  Ariel asked. \'93Will his emotional state be normal again?\'94\par
\'93We will have to wait for data about that question. He will sleep for many hours, yet,\'94 said Surgeon 1. \'93We will also have him mildly tranquilized when he first awakens. to guard against further shock when he finds himself fully human again.\'94\par
\'93If his body is truly recovering,\'94 said Research 1, \'93his serum levels in all cases should gradually return to normal. I surmise that the effect will not be immediate, but our information is poor on this subject.\'94\par
Ariel nodded.\par
\'93We\'92ll be moving along,\'94 said Derec. \'93I\'92m going to get on the central computer and see about refurbishing a certain little spacecraft. Also, how many further modifications it might take.  Keep us up to date on Jeff through my console, all right?\'94\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER 18\par
LIFT-OFF\par
\par
Derec was able to assemble a work crew of function robots to take care of the spacecraft under Mandelbrot\'92s direction. The computer released them from normal du,ty with the understanding that Ariel\'92s welfare would be aided by her leaving the planet. It was not exactly a clear First Law requirement, but in the absence of significant objections, it was sufficient.\par
Derec was disappointed to learn that the ship would not support the modifications required to support a second human passenger, but he was not surprised. The entire craft was just too small.  He and Ariel had watched the robots construct a hangar near where Mandelbrot had landed it, in which minor repairs could be made. He followed the robots\'92 progress with a certain intellectual interest.\par
Ariel did not seem to like talking about the ship, or where she would go in it. He understood that Aurora was off-limits, and neither of them really knew where she might reasonably look for a cure. Anyway, she wouldn\'92t discuss it.\par
She brightened for the first time when Research 1 called through the computer console. He told Derec that Jeff was alert, talking, and no longer drugged, for the first time since his body had been restored. She insisted that she and Derec visit him right away.\par
They found Jeff lying on an air cushion, wearing a soft, loose gown that billowed gently around him. Research 1 had told them that Jeff was self-conscious about the numerous scars he now bore, though they could be largely eliminated by further procedures later on.  Derec looked at Jeff\'92s slender body and Asian face and thought he looked more as though he was Derec\'92s age than eighteen.\par
Jeff\'92s dark eyes darted back and forth suspiciously between them. He said nothing.\par
\'93How are you?\'94 Ariel asked.\par
Jeff looked at her without speaking for a long moment. \'93Human,\'94 he said quietly. \'93I guess.\'94\par
\'93Feeling better?\'94 Derec asked.  Jeff shrugged shyly.\par
\'93Are you angry?\'94 Ariel asked.\par
\'93About what?\'94 Jeff said cautiously.\par
Derec looked uncomfortably at Ariel. He hadn\'92t spoken to Jeff as often as she had, and didn\'92t know how to approach him.\par
\'93You\'92re not a robot any more,\'94  she said.\par
Jeff shook his head almost imperceptibly. \'93I, uh...feel like I\'92ve been in a fog, or something. Like I\'92ve been dreaming. Almost like it wasn\'92t real. I remember it, I guess....\'94 He looked up at them both sharply, watching for their reactions.\par
Derec looked at Ariel again.\par
\'93You think I\'92m lying?\'94 Jeff\'92s voice had a hint of familiar belligerence. \'93You think I\'92m just trying to duck responsibility, I suppose. Why don\'92t you get out of here?\'94\par
\'93Come on,\'94 Ariel said quietly,  tugging at Derec\'92s sleeve. \'93Let\'92s leave him alone.\'94\par
Ariel led Derec into what had been the testing room. The original equipment had been put back into it, but it was still an adequate place to talk, especially since Jeff no longer had robotic hearing.\par
\'93We have to send him, not me,\'94  Ariel said bluntly.\par
\'93What?\'94 Derec straightened in surprise.\par
\'93He\'92s got to be the one to go.\'94\par
\'93He can wait, just like I\'92ll have to. Ariel, you\'92re the one who needs a cure. If Jeff knew that, he might not object, either.\'94\par
\'93Derec, did you see how he looked at us? He\'92s not over his\'97ordeal. He still thinks we\'92re out to get him in some way.\'94\par
\'93If you go, then he and I will get acquainted. We\'92ll make friends eventually, like you and I did. We\'92ll practically have to, being the only humans on the planet.\'94\par
\'93No, Derec. We have to prove to him that we don\'92t have a grudge\'97that people will help others just because they need it, and not because they\'92re going to get something selfish out of it.\'94\par
\'93Then let him prove it by helping you! You need to go worse than he does. That should be the basis for the decision.\'94\par
\'93Maybe I shouldn\'92t go, at least not yet.\'94\par
\'93What? What do you mean, you shouldn\'92t go?\'94\par
\'93Derec, I don\'92t know where to look for a cure. I could just go out and wander, but that\'92s not very reliable.  Maybe if I stay here, Research 1 could take a culture from me and get to work on a cure. It might take a long time, but it would be a chance.\'94\par
He hesitated, and looked at the unidentifiable equipment around the room. \'93The level of medical knowledge here is pretty erratic...but I guess the First Law might require him to try.\'94\par
\'93And once that\'92s set up, then I could take the next chance I had to leave. \'93\par
\'93You could leave a culture with Research 1 now and go yourself.\'94\par
\'93Leaving Jeff here that way just doesn\'92t seem fair.\'94 She shook her head. \'93Besides, it would just help convince him that we\'92re only out for ourselves.\'94\par
\'93Is that the only reason?\'94\par
\'93Well, no.\'94 She looked away,  smiling with embarrassment. \'93Anyway, why are you trying so hard to get rid of me?\'94\par
Derec folded his arms and shrugged. \'93Do you remember right after we first got here? I told you that I would stay to help the robots as they had asked, but that we could ask them to send you away.\'94\par
\'93I told you I would stay with you.\'94 She nodded.\par
\'93Well, I\'92ve always been glad you decided to stay, but...I figure it would be better for you to go, that\'92s all.\'94  He shrugged again, feeling his face grow hot.\par
\'93You want me to stay with you,  don\'92t you?\'94 She had to bend down a little to get under his lowered gaze, and she gave him a playful, knowing smile. \'93Don\'92t you?\'94\par
\'93Well....\'94 He couldn\'92t keep from smiling himself, but he was surprised when she put her arms around him and gave him a long hug. \'93As long as I\'92m still stuck here, anyhow....\'94 He had just recovered enough to hug her back when she patted him and pulled away.\par
She laughed. \'93Come on. Let\'92s go tell him.\'94\par
\par
Jeff held the highly polished rectangle of metal in one hand and angled it so he could see himself. Research 1 had provided it in answer to his request for a mirror; the robots had not possessed, or ever desired, a personal mirror. He ran his hand along his jaw,  then gently squeezed his cheeks so that his mouth puffed out. Then he smiled faintly at the face and wiggled his eyebrows up and down.\par
\'93It\'92s you again,\'94 he said,  almost in a whisper. \'93It\'92s me again.\'94 He was losing the impulse to talk to himself, though, so he quit.\par
Still, he couldn\'92t stop looking in his mirror. This was him, like he was supposed to be. He was back again.  Jeff Leong, the eighteen-year-old, was alive and getting better, if not exactly well yet.\par
At the sound of a knock, he lowered the mirror. \'93Yeah?\'94 He said quietly.\par
The door opened just enough for Ariel to stick her head inside. \'93We have to tell you something.\'94\par
Jeff tensed. \'93Yeah?\'94\par
She and Derec entered the room.  \'93We just wanted to let you know that as soon as you\'92re well enough, we have a spacecraft that can take you off the planet. Depending on how fast you recover, you might still make the start of the new semester.\'94\par
He studied their faces for a moment. \'93How much?\'94\par
Ariel looked at him,  uncomprehending.\par
\'93It\'92s free,\'94 said Derec.\par
\'93You\'92re going to give me a spacecraft, supplies, and fuel for free? What do you want me to do for you?\'94\par
\'93Nothing!\'94 Derec said angrily.  \'93Listen, why\'97\'94\par
She stopped him with a hand on his arm. \'93Jeff, you can consider it a loan, if you like. As a matter of fact,  if you could send someone back to pick us up someday\'97we don\'92t have any money,  either, and I know you don\'92t\'97but if you ever got the chance to do that, it would be more than enough repayment.\'94\par
\'93I\'92m no navigator,\'94 said Jeff.  \'93I don\'92t suppose I could send anyone back here, or even find it myself. I guess I should tell you that.\'94 He watched them closely, expecting them to change their minds.\par
\'93Fair enough,\'94 said Ariel. \'93We know that Mandelbrot lost his data when he stopped being Alpha, so he can\'92t help, either.\'94\par
Jeff shifted his gaze to Derec.\par
\'93When you\'92re well enough, it\'92s all yours.\'94 Derec nodded.\par
Jeff looked at them both without speaking, not sure whether to believe them or not. From the moment he had first awakened on this planet, virtually nothing that he had seen, heard, or done had been believable. This was no different.\par
\'93Did you hear what we said?\'94  Ariel asked.\par
\'93Yeah.\'94 His voice was low and wary.\par
They looked at each other uncertainly. He watched them, not sure what to expect. Then, without further comment, they left.\par
\par
Jeff\'92s physical recovery progressed well, and Derec suspected that the First Law made his robot medical team more cautious and conservative in their judgments than human doctors would have been. Still, even when it was clear that his brain had been successfully transplanted, his bodily injuries also had to heal. He remained quiet and wary in his manner, but he was no longer egotistical or insulting. Ariel noticed that that behavior had vanished with his robot body.\par
Derec suggested to Ariel that they form a farewell gathering for Jeff\'92s lift-off. Once he had recovered enough to travel, Mandelbrot set the computer in the little ship and gave him a quick course in its manual controls, in the event of emergency. Basically, the computer was to locate the nearest spacelane and wait there, sending a continuous distress signal. No one, including the robots, questioned that in a major spacelane he would be picked up before his life-support ran out.\par
Jeff remained quiet and cautious even as he was about to leave, but Research 1 was certain that the physical effects of his experience were wearing off.\par
\'93He has been integrated with his body for some time now,\'94 said Research 1. \'93His serum levels are his own.\'94\par
As they stood near the hangar waiting for Jeff to enter the ship, Ariel added, \'93After he\'92s back in normal human society again, I\'92m sure he\'92ll be okay.\'94\par
\'93He hasn\'92t acted very grateful,\'94  said Derec. \'93After all, we don\'92t have to send him. Both of us want to get out of here, too.\'94\par
\'93Shh,\'94 said Ariel.\par
Jeff walked up to them. He still moved slowly and tentatively sometimes, but he was fully mobile now. \'93I just wanted to tell you that if I can figure out where this planet is, I\'92ll get word to some emergency people.\'94\par
\'93I know you will,\'94 said Ariel.  \'93Have a good trip.\'94\par
\'93And thanks for the, uh, chance to go.\'94 He looked away shyly.\par
\'93It\'92s all right,\'94 said Derec.  \'93Take care of yourself.\'94\par
Jeff looked up at Research 1 and Surgeon 1 with a slight grin. \'93Well, it\'92s certainly been interesting knowing you two. Thanks for getting me all back together. \'93\par
\'93You are welcome,\'94 they said in unison.\par
He looked around at them all,  and stopped at Wolruf. \'93You okay, kiddo?\'94\par
\'93Okay,\'94 said Wolruf, with a furry nod that quivered her pointed ears. \'93 \'91U be careful on \'91urr trip.\'94\par
\'93Well...good-bye.\'94 Jeff nodded awkwardly and joined Mandelbrot at the ship. The robot would make sure he was properly prepared for lift-off.\par
Moments later, he was in the ship and it was roaring away, ascending quickly into the sky until it was only a sliver of light reflected from the sun.\par
Derec watched it rise, squinting into the deep sky until the back of his neck hurt from the strain. \'93Our one greatest wish,\'94 he said. \'93And we gave it away.\'94\par
Ariel took his arm in both her hands and leaned against him. \'93We did right, Derec. Besides, we aren\'92t through yet.\'94\par
He looked down at her and grinned. \'93Not us\'97not by a long shot.\'94\par
Together, they turned and led the little group back toward Robot City.\par
